-- | The Types module aims at providing a representation for (first-order)
--   monomorphic Haskell types. Two type representations are equal if and
--   only if the represented types have identical definitions. Thus a type
--   representation consists of a type term and the smallest list of all
--   (data or newtype) definitions needed either in the type term or in
--   another definition. The list of definitions is sorted to make
--   representations unique.
--   
--   The main use of type representations is to provide a type index for
--   storing Haskell values externally and for reading them back into a
--   running program without sacrificing type safety. Just reading them
--   back with the <tt>Read</tt> class is not sufficient because
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>Read</tt> does not distinguish between <tt>Int</tt> and
--   <tt>Integer</tt>, <tt>Float</tt> and <tt>Double</tt>y</li>
--   <li><tt>Read</tt> cannot avoid accidental matches of constructor
--   names</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   Meanwhile, the <tt>Data.Typeable</tt> class of GHC provides an
--   encoding with similar goals.
module WASH.CGI.Types

-- | A type specification consists of a type representation <a>TyRep</a>
--   and a list of type declarations.
data TySpec
TS :: TyRep -> [TyDecl] -> TySpec

-- | A type representation is built from base types, type variables,
--   tuples, and references to data-defined types.
data TyRep
TRBase :: String -> TyRep
TRVar :: String -> TyRep
TRTuple :: [TyRep] -> TyRep
TRData :: String -> [TyRep] -> TyRep

-- | A data declaration consists of the name of the data type, a list of
--   type variables, and a list of constructor representations.
data TyDecl

-- | A constructor is represented by its name, a list of field names (if
--   defined using record notation), and the list of its argument types

-- | type of handles to a PE of type <tt>a</tt>
data T a

-- | <tt>check name</tt> returns the current handle to cookie <tt>name</tt>
--   if that exists.
check :: (Read a, Show a, Types a) => String -> CGI (Maybe (T a))

-- | <tt>create name initValue</tt> creates cookie <tt>name</tt> with
--   initial value <tt>initValue</tt> and returns its current handle. The
--   cookie expires at the end of the current run of the browser.
create :: (Read a, Show a, Types a) => String -> a -> CGI (T a)

-- | like <a>create</a> with additional parameter specifying number of
--   minutes until cookie expires.
createExpiring :: (Read a, Show a, Types a) => String -> Int -> a -> CGI (T a)

-- | <tt>init name initValue</tt> returns current handle to cookie
--   <tt>name</tt>. If the cookie did not exist before, it is created and
--   set to <tt>initialValue</tt>. The cookie expires at the end of the
--   current run of the browser.
init :: (Read a, Show a, Types a) => String -> a -> CGI (T a)

-- | <tt>initExpiring name minutes initValue</tt> works like <a>init</a>
--   except that the expiration time is <tt>minutes</tt> in the future.
initExpiring :: (Read a, Show a, Types a) => String -> Int -> a -> CGI (T a)

-- | <tt>get handle</tt> returns the cookie's value if the handle is
--   current, otherwise returns <a>Nothing</a>
get :: (Read a, Show a, Types a) => T a -> CGI (Maybe a)

-- | <tt>set handle newValue</tt> overwrites the cookie's value with
--   <tt>newValue</tt> if the handle is current. In that case it returns a
--   handle which is current for <tt>newValue</tt>. Otherwise, the result
--   is <a>Nothing</a>.
set :: (Read a, Show a, Types a) => T a -> a -> CGI (Maybe (T a))

-- | <tt>current handle</tt> returns <tt>Nothing</tt> if <tt>handle</tt> is

--   <tt>newHandle</tt> is current for the cookie pointed to by
--   <tt>handle</tt>.
current :: (Read a, Show a, Types a) => T a -> CGI (Maybe (T a))

-- | <tt>delete handle</tt> removes the cookie determined by
--   <tt>handle</tt>.

-- | This is the preferred, type-indexed implementation of server-side
--   state.
--   
--   Glossary
--   
--   A persistent entity (PE) is a time-indexed, named global value. The
--   current value of a PE is the value that the PE has now. A handle gives
--   access to a snapshot of a persistent entity at a particular time,
--   potentially in the past. A handle is <i>current</i> if the value of
--   the PE has not been <tt>set</tt> or <tt>add</tt>ed to after the
--   creation of the handle.
module WASH.CGI.Persistent2

-- | type of handles to a PE of type <tt>a</tt>
data T a

-- | <tt>init name initialValue</tt> creates a new PE with name
--   <tt>name</tt> with initial value <tt>initialValue</tt> and returns the
--   handle to the initial value. If the PE already exists, then
--   <tt>init</tt> returns the handle to the current value.
init :: (Read a, Show a, Types a) => String -> a -> CGI (T a)

-- | <tt>get handle</tt> retrieves the value of <tt>handle</tt>. This value
--   may not be current because the handle may point to a snapshot from the
--   past.
get :: (Read a, Types a) => T a -> CGI a

-- | <tt>set handle newValue</tt> tries to overwrite the value of the pe
--   pointed to by <tt>handle</tt> with <tt>newValue</tt>. Succeeds
--   <tt>Just handle1</tt> if <tt>handle</tt> is current, in this case it
--   returns a handle to the new value. Fails <tt>Nothing</tt> if the
--   handle is not current.
set :: (Read a, Show a, Types a) => T a -> a -> CGI (Maybe (T a))

-- | <tt>add handle addValue</tt> conceptually, this operation adds
--   <tt>addValue</tt> to the set of values stored in <tt>handle</tt>.
--   Since this set is represented as a list, <tt>handle</tt> must point to
--   a value of type <tt>[a]</tt>. Since the PE is assumed to contain a
--   set, it does not matter if <tt>handle</tt> is current. However, the
--   returned handle is guaranteed to be current with a value that contains
--   <tt>addValue</tt>.
add :: (Read a, Show a, Types a) => T [a] -> a -> CGI (T [a])

-- | <tt>current handle</tt> returns a handle to the PE pointed to by
--   <tt>handle</tt>. It returns <tt>Nothing</tt> if <tt>handle</tt> is
--   still <i>current</i>. Otherwise, it returns <tt>Just newHandle</tt>
--   where <tt>newHandle</tt> is <i>current</i> in the sense defined above.
--   Using the <tt>newHandle</tt> obtained from <tt>current</tt> explicitly
--   discards the value pointed to by <tt>handle</tt> in favor of a value
--   that may have been stored by a concurrently executing script. Use with
--   caution!
current :: (Read a, Types a) => T a -> CGI (Maybe (T a))

-- | Transactional, type-indexed implementation of server-side state.
--   
--   Glossary
--   
--   A transactional entity (TE) is a named multi-versioned global
--   variable.
module WASH.CGI.Transaction

-- | Handle of a transactional variable
data T a

-- | Attempt to create a new tv <tt>n</tt> and set its initial value.
--   Returns handle to the variable. If the variable already exists, then
--   just returns the handle.
init :: (Types a, Read a, Show a) => String -> a -> TCGI b (T a)

-- | Create a fresh transactional variable with an initial value and return
--   its handle. Performs a physical write to ensure that the variable's
--   name is unique. Locks the transaction directory during the write
--   operation.
create :: (Read a, Show a, Types a) => a -> TCGI b (T a)

-- | Remove a transactional variable. Subsequent read accesses to this
--   variable will make the transaction fail. May throw an exception if the
--   variable is not present.
remove :: Types a => T a -> TCGI b ()

-- | Read transactional variable through a typed handle.
get :: (Read a, Show a) => T a -> TCGI b a

-- | Write to a transactional variable through typed handle. Only affects
--   the log, no <i>physical</i> write happens. Checks physically for
--   existence of the variable (but tries the log first). Raises exception
--   if it does not exist.
set :: (Read a, Show a) => T a -> a -> TCGI b ()
with :: (WithMonad cgi, Read result, Show result) => result -> (result -> cgi ()) -> (Control (TCGI result) result -> (TCGI result) ()) -> cgi ()
data Control cgi result
Control :: (result -> cgi ()) -> (result -> cgi ()) -> (result -> cgi ()) -> Control cgi result

-- | abandon with result (rollback)
abandon :: Control cgi result -> result -> cgi ()

-- | set result on failure
setFail :: Control cgi result -> result -> cgi ()

-- | set result on successful commit
setCommit :: Control cgi result -> result -> cgi ()

-- | Type of a <a>CGI</a> action in a transactional scope with a result
--   variable of type <tt>a</tt>.
data TCGI b a
instance Show TV_DESC
instance Read (T a)
instance Show (T a)
instance WithMonad (TCGI x)
instance WithMonad CGI
